platinum group metal, extraction and refinery operations
coeff_comments: (Dobson and Burgess, 2007) described: The Livingston (1992) study, as summarized in Dobson & Burgess (2007), demonstrated a >99% removal efficiency for 3-chloronitrobenzene, a chlorine-containing compound, in an MBR. This is achieved through microbial degradation that releases chlorine as chloride ions, which are significantly less harmful and more stable in water. The efficient separation and retention of microorganisms within the reactor ensure thorough treatment, allowing MBRs to consistently handle various pollutants, including chlorinated compound. The broader removal efficiencies for contaminants in municipal and industrial wastewater reported by Melin et al. (2006) include total suspended solids (>99%), biological oxygen demand (>97%), and chemical oxygen demand (89–98%). These figures indicate that MBRs provide high treatment performance across a range of pollutants, including dissolved organic and inorganic species.

coeff_comments: Selenium, like sulfur, often volatilizes as selenium dioxide (SeO₂) during high-temperature smelting and roasting, following similar pathways for emission and mitigation. The implementation of advanced control measures like FGD combined with electrostatic demisters (ESD) achieves up to 97% reduction in SOx emissions. Selenium, which shares solubility and chemical behavior with SO₃, will likely have similar removal rates

coeff_comments:
The commercial tests of the two_x0002_stage noncatalytic
process of gas cleaning were performed in a heating
furnace (intended for heating the feed of a vacuum
column) at an oil refinery in Haifa (Israel). The vol_x0002_
ume of flue gases released from the furnace was
25000–30000 m 3/h (NTP). The concentration of
nitrogen oxides in the flue gases (in terms of NO 2 at an
oxygen content to 3 vol %) was 500–550 mg/m 3
(NTP) [(244–268) × 10–4%].
The reducing mixture obtained as a result of the
thermal decomposition of an aqueous solution of urea
was introduced into the high_x0002_temperature zone of the
furnace with a flue gas temperature of 905–960°C.
The above mixture but activated with an additive was
placed in the low_x0002_temperature zone of the furnace with
a flue gas temperature of 410–420°C. As a result of the
two_x0002_stage process of gas cleaning, the concentration of
nitrogen oxides was decreased to 20–35 mg/m3
[(10⎯ 17) × 10 –4%]. Thus, the total efficiency of the
purification of flue gases ejected from the heating fur_x0002_
nace was 94–96% Fig. 2
coeff_tech: Suppression of the formation of nitrogen oxides

platinum group metal, extraction and refinery operations
sub_compartment: non-urban air or from high stacks
coeff_comments:
The commercial tests of the two_x0002_stage noncatalytic
process of gas cleaning were performed in a heating
furnace (intended for heating the feed of a vacuum
column) at an oil refinery in Haifa (Israel). The vol_x0002_
ume of flue gases released from the furnace was
25000–30000 m 3/h (NTP). The concentration of
nitrogen oxides in the flue gases (in terms of NO 2 at an
oxygen content to 3 vol %) was 500–550 mg/m 3
(NTP) [(244–268) × 10–4%].
The reducing mixture obtained as a result of the
thermal decomposition of an aqueous solution of urea
was introduced into the high_x0002_temperature zone of the
furnace with a flue gas temperature of 905–960°C.
The above mixture but activated with an additive was
placed in the low_x0002_temperature zone of the furnace with
a flue gas temperature of 410–420°C. As a result of the
two_x0002_stage process of gas cleaning, the concentration of
nitrogen oxides was decreased to 20–35 mg/m3
[(10⎯ 17) × 10 –4%]. Thus, the total efficiency of the
purification of flue gases ejected from the heating fur_x0002_
nace was 94–96% Fig. 2
coeff_tech: Suppression of the formation of nitrogen oxides
